Lab: Enable Developer Self-service
1️⃣ Goal of the Lab
You configure OpenShift so that every new project automatically has resource restrictions.
Restrictions:
Project Level (Quota)
Resource	Limit
Total memory requests	2 Gi
Total memory limits	4 Gi
Meaning:
All workloads in the project together cannot exceed these totals.
________________________________________
Container Level (LimitRange)
Every container must follow:
Property	Value
Min memory	128 Mi
Default request	256 Mi
Default limit	512 Mi
Max memory	1 Gi
Meaning:
Each container has its own limit, and the project also has total limits.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Lab Preparation
Run:
lab start selfservice-review
This prepares:
•	OpenShift cluster
•	required lab files
•	configuration files
________________________________________
3️⃣ Login as Admin
oc login -u admin -p redhatocp https://api.ocp4.example.com:6443
Purpose:
Admin is needed to:
•	create project templates
•	configure cluster settings
________________________________________
4️⃣ Create Namespace to Design Template
Namespace:
oc create namespace template-test
Purpose:
We first design and test configuration in a namespace before putting it in a template.
Think of it like:
Testing area → then production template
________________________________________
5️⃣ Create ResourceQuota
Command:
oc create quota memory \
--hard=requests.memory=2Gi,limits.memory=4Gi \
-n template-test
What is ResourceQuota?
ResourceQuota limits total resources used by a project.
Example:
If quota is:
requests.memory = 2Gi
Then all pods combined cannot request more than 2Gi memory.
________________________________________
Explanation of command
oc create quota memory
Creates quota named memory.
--hard=requests.memory=2Gi
Total memory requested by all pods cannot exceed 2Gi.
limits.memory=4Gi
Total memory limits cannot exceed 4Gi.
________________________________________
6️⃣ Create LimitRange
Edit file:
~/DO280/labs/selfservice-review/limitrange.yaml
Final configuration:
apiVersion: v1
kind: LimitRange
metadata:
  name: memory
  namespace: template-test
spec:
  limits:
  - min:
      memory: 128Mi
    defaultRequest:
      memory: 256Mi
    default:
      memory: 512Mi
    max:
      memory: 1Gi
    type: Container
________________________________________
What is LimitRange?
LimitRange controls per-container limits.
Example:
Rule	Meaning
min	container must request ≥128Mi
defaultRequest	default memory request
default	default memory limit
max	cannot exceed 1Gi
________________________________________
Create the LimitRange
oc create -f ~/DO280/labs/selfservice-review/limitrange.yaml
Now the namespace has:
ResourceQuota
LimitRange
________________________________________
7️⃣ Test LimitRange
Create deployment:
oc create deployment -n template-test test-limits \
--image registry.ocp4.example.com:8443/redhattraining/hello-world-nginx:v1.0
This deployment does not specify resources.
But LimitRange automatically applies defaults.
Check:
oc get pod -n template-test \
-o jsonpath='{.items[0].spec.containers[0].resources}'
Output:
limits.memory = 512Mi
requests.memory = 256Mi
Meaning:
LimitRange automatically added:
request = 256Mi
limit = 512Mi
________________________________________
8️⃣ Test ResourceQuota
Scale deployment:
oc scale deployment -n template-test test-limits --replicas=10
Each pod uses:
request = 256Mi
limit = 512Mi
Now calculate.
________________________________________
Memory Requests
256Mi × 8 pods = 2Gi
Quota reached.
________________________________________
Memory Limits
512Mi × 8 pods = 4Gi
Quota reached.
________________________________________
So deployment runs only 8 pods instead of 10.
Check:
oc get deployment -n template-test
Result:
READY 8/10
________________________________________
Check quota
oc describe resourcequota -n template-test
Output:
limits.memory    4Gi
requests.memory  2Gi
Meaning:
Quota fully used.
________________________________________
9️⃣ Create Project Template
Generate template:
oc adm create-bootstrap-project-template \
-o yaml > ~/DO280/labs/selfservice-review/template.yaml
This generates default project template.
________________________________________
🔟 Add LimitRange and ResourceQuota
Export resources:
oc get limitrange,quota -n template-test -o yaml
Copy objects and add them to template.
Important modifications:
Remove:
creationTimestamp
resourceVersion
uid
status
Replace namespace:
template-test
with
${PROJECT_NAME}
Why?
Because the template must work for any project name.
________________________________________
1️⃣1️⃣ Final Template Structure
Template includes:
Object	Purpose
Project	create namespace
RoleBinding	give admin access
LimitRange	container limits
ResourceQuota	project limits
________________________________________
1️⃣2️⃣ Create Template in Cluster
oc create \
-f ~/DO280/labs/selfservice-review/template.yaml \
-n openshift-config
Namespace:
openshift-config
This namespace stores cluster configuration templates.
________________________________________
1️⃣3️⃣ Configure Cluster to Use Template
Edit:
oc edit projects.config.openshift.io cluster
Add:
spec:
  projectRequestTemplate:
    name: project-request
Meaning:
Whenever someone runs:
oc new-project
OpenShift applies this template.
________________________________________
1️⃣4️⃣ API Server Restart
Check restart:
watch oc get pod -n openshift-apiserver
Wait until pods show:
Running
This means configuration is applied.
________________________________________
1️⃣5️⃣ Test the Template
Create project:
oc new-project template-validate
Now OpenShift automatically creates:
LimitRange
ResourceQuota
RoleBinding
________________________________________
1️⃣6️⃣ Verify Quota
oc describe quota
Output:
limits.memory    4Gi
requests.memory  2Gi
________________________________________
1️⃣7️⃣ Verify LimitRange
oc describe limitrange
Output:
Min: 128Mi
Default Request: 256Mi
Default Limit: 512Mi
Max: 1Gi
________________________________________
1️⃣8️⃣ Final Architecture
Flow when user creates project:
User
  ↓
oc new-project
  ↓
ProjectRequest
  ↓
Project Template
  ↓
Creates:
  Namespace
  RoleBinding
  LimitRange
  ResourceQuota
